{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015hdfyigRKVrdmWwaBMCazo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error is `Can't find a node_ip_address.json file from /tmp/ray/session_...`. \n\nThis means Ray is connecting but it's trying to look for a local session file. The address `ray-head:6379` connects to Redis but then tries to find a local node_ip_address.json which doesn't exist on the client pod.\n\nThe issue is that `ray.init(address=\"ray-head:6379\")` is the old way to connect to Ray, but it seems this version of Ray (2.9.0) expects a different approach.\n\nLet me check the Ray services to understand the setup better and what address format to use.\nI'm realizing that `ray-head:6379` is actually the GCS address in Ray 2.x, not just Redis. The proper way to connect would be using `ray://ray-head:10001` for the Ray Client server, which uses gRPC instead of the older Redis-based approach.\n\nThe real problem is that the client pod is trying to initialize itself as a Ray worker node when it should just be connecting as a client to the existing cluster. Since it's not actually part of the Ray cluster network, it can't find the local node configuration files it expects. I need to check what ports the ray-head service is actually exposing and verify the Ray cluster version to understand the correct connection method.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1267,"cache_read_input_tokens":38656,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1267},"output_tokens":41,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1fbf2895-253f-4b32-a4d0-58f3f429940b","uuid":"66426b57-cb6b-492a-ad15-71e2b52b8a67","request_id":"req_011Cc6iLVjfmwDCG1EyxMGka"}
