{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01P8HreH6hoWojsU4YUZFKZq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The service only exposes ports 6379 (GCS/Redis) and 8265 (dashboard). There's no port 10001 (Ray Client). So Ray Client mode (`ray://ray-head:10001`) will timeout because that port isn't exposed.\n\nThe address `ray-head:6379` connects to GCS, which is the correct format for Ray 2.x internal connections. But when Ray tries to connect as a worker (not just a client), it needs to have `node_ip_address.json` which is a local session file.\n\nLet me look at how the head node was started. The issue might be that:\n1. The Ray client pod needs to be set up differently \n2. Or we need to use a different approach\n\nLooking at the error more carefully, the connection to `ray-head:6379` is succeeding, but Ray can't find the session file it expects at `/tmp/ray/session_2026-06-16_02-26-35_897098_13`, which means the worker initialization is failing because it's missing the local node configuration.\n\nThe issue is that when using `ray.init(address=\"<gcs_address>\")`, Ray expects to join as a worker node, which requires the Ray runtime to already be initialized locally on that pod. The pod would need to run `ray start --address=<gcs>` first to set up the local runtime before connecting to the cluster. Alternatively, using a `ray://` URI scheme might handle this differently.\n\nLooking at Ray 2.9.0 specifically, the connection behavior depends on the address format: `ray://` uses the Ray Client protocol over gRPC to port 10001, while a plain `host:port` format attempts to join the cluster as a worker node. Since port 10001 isn't exposed and the client pod isn't configured as a Ray worker, neither approach works directly as currently set up.\n\nBut the task explicitly specifies connecting to `ray-head:6379`, which suggests this might be the GCS (Global Control Store) port in an older Redis-based Ray configuration. I should check how the Ray head pod was actually started to understand if 6379 is the correct port to use.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":930,"cache_read_input_tokens":39923,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":930},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1fbf2895-253f-4b32-a4d0-58f3f429940b","uuid":"b11b1724-b44e-40e2-b7f3-8efbac1f971f","request_id":"req_011Cc6iMsQSDgCeSnLkY3XYh"}
